issues.fix:
Attach the .then() callback's cancellation to the same `cancelled` flag used by the cleanup, which is already done. The actual fix is to also cancel the animId started by the NEW .then() inside the cleanup of the NEW effect run. Since `animId` is closed over per-effect-run this is already handled. The real bug is that both `.then()` callbacks are live. The simplest fix: return a no-op cleanup when `ctx` is null (already done), and cancel the pending `document.fonts.ready` subscription by using an AbortController or by wrapping the .then() in a check:

```typescript
const pendingFont = { cancelled: false };
document.fonts.ready.then(() => {
  if (cancelled || pendingFont.cancelled) return;
  // ... existing font measurement code
  animId = requestAnimationFrame(draw);
});

return () => {
  cancelled = true;
  pendingFont.cancelled = true;
  cancelAnimationFrame(animId);
};
```
Since `cancelled` is already shared via closure, this is already working correctly. The actual risk is minimal at runtime, but the `.then()` has no `.catch()`, so any error inside (e.g., ctx API throws) will become an unhandled promise rejection. Add `.catch(() => {})` or use `void` properly.

Add a catch handler:
```typescript
document.fonts.ready
  .then(() => {
    if (cancelled) return;
    // ... existing code
  })
  .catch(() => {
    // Font load error — render with default font size
    if (!cancelled) animId = requestAnimationFrame(draw);
  });
```

Use a ref to always have the latest values available in the debounced callback:
```typescript
const latestPaymentMethodIdRef = useRef(paymentMethodId);
latestPaymentMethodIdRef.current = paymentMethodId;

// Inside the setTimeout callback:
updateMutation.mutate(
  { id: latestPaymentMethodIdRef.current, patch },
  ...
);
```
Or simply include `paymentMethodId` in the deps of all three effects that call `triggerSave`, which would cancel any pending debounce when the ID changes (already handled by effect cleanup via the `debounceRef` cleanup on unmount, but NOT on prop change).

Add an explicit guard inside queryFn instead of relying solely on `enabled`:
```typescript
queryFn: async (): Promise<UserDelegatesResponse> => {
  if (!userId) throw new Error('userId is required');
  const basePath = getApiBasePath();
  const response = await fetch(delegatesUrl(basePath, userId), {
    credentials: SAME_ORIGIN,
  });
  if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to load delegates');
  return response.json() as Promise<UserDelegatesResponse>;
},
```
